ollege inaccessible to a large share of students of color, and reveals how policies that acknowledge racial inequalities and set racial equality goals can succeed where colorblindness has failed.Gary Orfield paints a troubling portrait of American higher education, explaining how profound racial gaps imbedded in virtually every stage of our children’s lives pose a major threat to communities of color and the nation. He describes how the l960s and early 1970s was the only period in history to witness sustained efforts at racial equity in higher education, and how the Reagan era ushered in today’s colorblind policies, which ignore the realities of color inequality. Orfield shows how this misguided policy has resegregated public schools, exacerbated inequalities in college preparation, denied needed financial aid to families, and led to huge price increases over decades that have seen little real gain in income for most Americans.Drawing on a wealth of new data and featuring commentaries by Stella Flores and James Anderson, this timely and urgent book shows how colorblind policies serve only to raise the walls of segregation higher, and proposes real solutions that can make higher education available to all.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAffirmative action programs in educationzUnited States. 0aEducational equalizationzUnited States. 0aHigher education and statezUnited States. 0aMinority college studentszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aUniversities and collegeszUnited StatesxAdmission. 7aEDUCATION / Higher.2bisacsh  a1960s and early 1970s.  aGary Orfield.  aJames Anderson.  aPrinceton University Press.  aRace, Justice & Equity.  aStella Flores.  aThe Failure of Colorblind Policy for Higher Education.  aThe Walls around Opportunity.  aThe case for race-conscious education policy.  